**H2 Structure:**

1. **What You'll Need Before You Start (and What Actually Matters)**
   *(Tools and supplies — but framed as "here's what makes a real difference" not a flat shopping list. Distinguish must-haves from nice-to-haves. White polish formula guidance here — self-levelling, thin-formula, not chalky. Key AEO target: "what tools do I need for a french manicure at home.")*

2. **Choose Your Method First: Tape, Guides, Freehand, or Stamper?**
   *(The unique differentiator — the method-choice section that no competitor offers. Four H3s: one per method. Brief description, skill level requirement, result quality, and who it's best for. Readers choose their path BEFORE starting. This is the single biggest gap in all competitor content.)*
   - H3: Nail Tape — the most accessible method for beginners
   - H3: French Tip Sticker Guides — the most foolproof option
   - H3: Freehand with a Liner Brush — for the steady-handed
   - H3: Silicone Stamper — the viral TikTok method that actually works

3. **Step-by-Step: How to Do a French Manicure at Home**
   *(The core tutorial — numbered steps, clear sequencing, timing at every step. Six to eight numbered steps: dehydrate/prep, shape and buff, base coat, tip application [method-specific], sheer pink/nude coat, top coat, cleanup, cuticle oil. Each step includes one sentence on WHY it matters and one on what goes wrong if skipped.)*

4. **The Tip Line: How to Get the Curved Smile Line Right**
   *(Dedicated section for the hardest step — pulled out of the main tutorial because it deserves full attention. Covers: the criss-cross brush stroke method, the correct angle to hold the brush, how to judge the right width, what "too thick" looks like vs. the modern thin tip. AEO target: "how do you get a clean line on french tips.")*

5. **Why Does My French Manicure Chip So Fast? (And How to Fix It)**
   *(The longevity section — explains the mechanism, not just the tips. Capping the free edge, thin coats, letting dry fully between coats, reapplying top coat every two days. Duration by format: regular polish 5–7 days, gel 2–3 weeks, dip 3–4 weeks. AEO target: "why does my french manicure chip so fast.")*

6. **Common French Manicure Mistakes — and How to Recover**
   *(Troubleshooting section — covers the four most common failures with specific fixes: wobbly line, muddy tip after applying pink coat, yellow or streaky white, polish lifting at edges. Acetone cleanup brush technique. This section is completely absent from all competitor guides.)*

7. **Can You Do a French Manicure on Short Nails?**
   *(Addresses one of the most searched questions in this topic. Yes — with specific guidance: thinner smile line, shorter tip width, oval or squoval shape works best. The micro French is actually easier on short nails. Links naturally to the micro-french-nails cluster post.)*

8. **The 2026 Update: How to Do a Modern French Tip at Home**
   *(Extends the tutorial for trend-aware readers — covers the micro French technique (thinner line, liner brush method) and colored tip option. Natural internal link to micro-french-nails and colored-french-tip-nails. Keeps the post future-relevant without drifting from tutorial intent.)*

